1070","1106":"1106","1125":"1125","1123":"1123","about 1100":"omkring 1100","1119":"1119","after 1125":"efter 1125","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Cornhill on Tweed, Northumberland, England":"Cornhill on Tweed, Northumberland, England","Jerusalem, Israel":"Jerusalem, Israel"},"nl":{"about 1070–1130":"circa 1070–1130","1070–1130":"1070–1130","1095–1130":"1095–1130","1060–Male":"1060–Overleden","1062–Male":"1062–Overleden","1123–1183":"1123–1183","1050–1125":"1050–1125","1050–Female":"1050–Overleden","about 1070":"circa 1070","1130":"1130","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1183":"1183","1062":"1062","1095":"1095","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","1070":"1070","1106":"1106","1125":"1125","1123":"1123","about 1100":"circa 1100","1119":"1119","after 1125":"na 1125","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Cornhill on Tweed, Northumberland, England":"Cornhill on Tweed, Northumberland, England","Jerusalem, Israel":"Jerusalem, Israël"},"en":{"about 1070–1130":"about 1070–1130","1070–1130":"1070–1130","1095–1130":"1095–1130","1060–Male":"1060–Deceased","1062–Male":"1062–Deceased","1123–1183":"1123–1183","1050–1125":"1050–1125","1050–Female":"1050–Deceased","about 1070":"about 1070","1130":"1130","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1183":"1183","1062":"1062","1095":"1095","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","1070":"1070","1106":"1106","1125":"1125","1123":"1123","about 1100":"about 1100","1119":"1119","after 1125":"after 1125","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Cornhill on Tweed, Northumberland, England":"Cornhill on Tweed, Northumberland, England","Jerusalem, Israel":"Jerusalem, Israel","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cornhill,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name in SE England mainly from Cornhill in London but elsewhere alternatively from Cornhill (Northumb) or one of the many minor places so called. It has often become   Cornell   and has sometimes been confused with   Cornwall  , and   Cornwell  , as in the case of Thomas Cornell, 1722 in   Parish Registers   (Horringer, Suffolk), who is also called Cornwall (1736), Cornwell (1740) and Cornhill (1766).","2  English:  see  Cornall  .","3  English:  see  Cornwall  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cornwall","meanings":["English:","habitational name from the county of Cornwall, which is named with the Old English tribal name <i>Cornwealas</i>. This is from <i>Kernow</i> (the term that the Cornish used to refer to themselves, a word of uncertain etymology, perhaps connected with a Celtic element meaning ‘horn, headland’), + Old English <i>wealas</i> ‘strangers, foreigners’, the term used by the Anglo-Saxons for British-speaking people.","variant of   Cornwell  ."]},{"name":"Parish Registers","meanings":["English:  see  Lonsdale  .   Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames   notes Tobias Londsdale or Lansdall, 1675–84 in   Parish Registers   (Keighley, WR Yorks)."]},{"name":"Cornwell","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Cornwell in Oxfordshire, named from Old English <i>corn</i>, a metathesized form of <i>cron</i>, <i>cran</i> ‘crane’ + <i>well(a)</i> ‘spring, stream’.","variant of   Cornwall   or <b>Cornhill</b>; in southeastern England mainly a habitational name from Cornhill in London but elsewhere alternatively from Cornhill (Northumberland) or one of the many minor places so called, often becoming   Cornell  ."]},{"name":"Cornell","meanings":["English: shortened form of   Cornwell  ,   Cornwall  , or of <b>Cornhill</b>, a habitational name from a place in Northumberland named Cornhill, from Old English <i>corn</i>, a metathesized form of <i>cron</i>, <i>cran</i> ‘crane’ + <i>halh</i> ‘nook, recess’; or from Cornhill in London, a medieval grain exchange, named with Old English <i>corn</i> ‘corn, grain’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’, or from some other place elsewhere similarly named.","English: variant of   Corney  .","English: possibly also a nickname from French <i>corneille</i> ‘rook, crow’, probably denoting a chatterer or someone with dark hair or a dark complexion."]},{"name":"Cornall","meanings":["1  English: the Lancs name is a variant of   Corney  , where  <i>-all</i> and  <i>-ell</i> are hypercorrect pronunciations of  <i>Cornah</i>,  <i>Corner</i>, and  <i>Cornoe</i>, late pronunciations of  <i>Corney</i>.","2  English: the Devon name is a variant of   Cornwall  . Here also probably belongs  <i>Gurnall</i>, as in Joan Gurnall, 1586 in   IGI   (Crediton, Devon), and William Gurnall, 1650 in   IGI   (Lavenham, Suffolk).  Compare  Corney  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":16,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":26,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":36,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger de Cornhill, Joint Sheriff of London was born about 1070, in Cornhill on Tweed, Northumberland, England, his father, Hubert de Cornhill, was 22 and his mother, Mrs. Hubert de Cornhill, was 22. He married Ingenolda de Conteville in 1119, in London, Middlesex, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. In 1125, at the age of 56, his occupation is listed as joint sheriff of london. He died in 1130, in Jerusalem, Israel, at the age of 61."},"et":{"about 1070–1130":"umbes 1070–1130","1070–1130":"1070–1130","1095–1130":"1095–1130","1060–Male":"1060–Surnud","1062–Male":"1062–Surnu